. Great shade tree. Type II pollinator. Pairs with Cape Fear, Creek. Late-season pollinizer. Water needs when young. Well-suited subtropical/commercial use.", "availability": "Australian nurseries"}, {"name": "CHOCTAW", "slug": "choctaw", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 15, "origin": "USDA 1950s-70s release, named after Choctaw Nation", "traits": "Large nuts, thin hull, resembles Western Schley appearance", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate, requires perfect management", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "KIOWA", "slug": "kiowa", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 16, "origin": "USDA 1976 (Mahan x Odom parentage, likely Mahan x Desirable)", "traits": "VERY LARGE nuts (45/lb), high-percentage kernel", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High yield potential, alternate bearing tendency", "growing_notes": "Late season maturity (late October-early November). Commonly recommended for Southeast U.S. Great scab resistance. Type A pollinator. Large size impressive but requires long growing season - suitable for humid subtropical climates if season length adequate. Commercial favorite for size/quality combination.", "availability": "Australian nurseries, commercial variety"}, {"name": "OCONEE", "slug": "oconee", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 17, "origin": "University of Georgia 1989 release", "traits": "Large nuts, cold-resistant, low-maintenance hybrid", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good, consistent", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "SIOUX", "slug": "sioux", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 18, "origin": "USDA (Schley x Carmichael cross)", "traits": "Small nuts, thin shell, very light color, gorgeous tree form", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good", "growing_notes": "ONE OF BEST EATING QUALITY - top flavor pecan. Small size excellent for mixed nut applications. Requires fungicide in HIGH HUMIDITY areas - humid subtropical climates would need sprays. Little training required - recommended best homeowner tree. Type A pollinator. Fresh flavor best in world. Native pecan flavor quality without hard shell.", "availability": "Specialty nurseries"}, {"name": "NATIVE/WILD PECANS", "slug": "native-wild-pecans", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 19, "origin": "Indigenous North America - discovered 16th century by European explorers, staple food for Native Americans since ancient times", "traits": "Variable size/shape (70-150/lb typical), thick hard shells, natural genetic diversity tree to tree", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Variable, no irrigation typically, rely on natural rainfall", "growing_notes": "INDIGENOUS HEIRLOOM - oldest pecan type. Algonquin word ''pacane'' = ''nut so hard requires stone to crack''. EXCELLENT disease resistance due to genetic variability. Heat-tolerant (especially Texas natives). Sustainable - no irrigation/fertilizer/spraying. Best for pecan pieces in candies/pralines/pies. Shell thickness natural protection from animals. Flavor superior to clones - stress improves taste. NOT suitable humid subtropical climates (requires sourcing from wild North American trees).", "availability": "NOT available Australia - U.S. wild harvest only (Texas, Missouri)"}], "variety_count": 20}'::jsonb,
